Cumulative anthropogenic (i.e., human-emitted) emissions of {{CO2}} from fossil fuel use are a major cause of [[global warming]],&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite journal| year = 2008
| author=Botzen, W.J.W.| title = Cumulative {{CO2}} emissions: shifting international responsibilities for climate debt| journal = Climate Policy| volume = 8| issue=6| doi = 10.3763/cpol.2008.0539| page = 570
|display-authors=etal}}
&lt;/ref&gt; and give some indication of which countries have contributed most to human-induced climate change.&lt;ref name="hohne 2010 regional contribution to global warming"&gt;
{{cite journal| date=24 September 2010| author=Höhne, N.| title=Contributions of individual countries' emissions to climate change and their uncertainty| journal=Climatic Change| doi=10.1007/s10584-010-9930-6| url=http://www.gcca.eu/usr/documents/Contributions_Individual_countries_201011229410.pdf| display-authors=etal| volume=106| issue=3| pages=359–91| url-status=dead| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426072941/http://www.gcca.eu/usr/documents/Contributions_Individual_countries_201011229410.pdf| archivedate=26 April 2012| df=dmy-all}}
&lt;/ref&gt;{{Rp|15}}

On March 9, 2017, in an interview on CNBC's [[Squawk Box]], Pruitt stated that he "would not agree that" carbon dioxide is "a primary contributor to the global warming that we see" backing up his claim by stating that "measuring with precision human activity on the climate is something very challenging to do and there's tremendous disagreement about the degree of impact."&lt;ref name="cnbc"&gt;{{cite web|last1=DiChristopher|first1=Tom|title=EPA chief Scott Pruitt says carbon dioxide is not a primary contributor to global warming|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2017/03/09/epa-chief-scott-pruitt.html|website=CNBC|publisher=NBC Universal |date=March 9, 2017|accessdate=March 9, 2017|ref=Pruitt believes Carbon Dioxide is not a contributor to Global Warming}}&lt;/ref&gt; This was in direct contradiction with EPA's public stance that was published on their official website which stated: "Carbon dioxide is the primary [[greenhouse gas]] that is contributing to recent climate change".&lt;ref name="nyt3"&gt;{{cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/us/politics/epa-scott-pruitt-global-warming.html | title=E.P.A. Chief Doubts Consensus View of Climate Change |author=Coral Davenport |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017| work=[[The New York Times]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; By April 28—the day before the [[People's Climate March (2017)|climate change mass protests]]—EPA announced that the website "would be 'undergoing changes' to better represent the new direction the agency is taking" which included "the removal of several agency websites containing detailed climate data and scientific information" including the site that "had been cited to challenge Pruitt's Squawk Box statements."&lt;ref name="wp_websiteremoved"&gt;{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/energy-environment/wp/2017/04/28/epa-website-removes-climate-science-site-from-public-view-after-two-decades/
|title=EPA website removes climate science site from public view after two decades
|first1=Chris |last1=Mooney |first2=Juliet |last2=Eilperin |date=April 29, 2017 |accessdate=April 30, 2017 |work=[[The Washington Post]]}}&lt;/ref&gt; A March 9 analysis by fact-checking website ''[[Snopes.com]]'' found that "Pruitt's statements to CNBC are misrepresentative of the scientific consensus on carbon dioxide's role as a greenhouse gas—a consensus that has essentially existed for more than a century."&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.snopes.com/2017/03/09/pruitt-global-warming-scientific-consensus/ |title=Do Scott Pruitt's Statements on CO2 and Global Warming Misrepresent Scientific Consensus? |publisher=Snopes.com |date= |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt; ''[[The Atlantic]]'' published an article on the same day, pointing out that in 2007, the [[United States Supreme Court]] had acknowledged the link between carbon dioxide and global warming—in 2013 the [[Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change]] stated the probability of carbon dioxide causing global warming was at least 95%.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite magazine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2017/03/trumps-epa-chief-rejects-that-carbon-dioxide-emissions-cause-climate-change/519054/ |title=Scott Pruitt Rejects the Scientific Fact of Climate Change |magazine=The Atlantic |date=March 9, 2017 |accessdate=March 24, 2017}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The '''Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change''' ('''IPCC''') is an [[intergovernmental organization|intergovernmental body]] of the [[United Nations]]&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web |title = About the IPCC | url = https://www.ipcc.ch/about/ |publisher = Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change | accessdate=22 February 2019}}
&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;
{{cite web |url = http://royalsociety.org/uploadedFiles/Royal_Society_Content/News_and_Issues/Science_Issues/Climate_change/climate_facts_and_fictions.pdf |title = A guide to facts and fictions about climate change|publisher=[[The Royal Society]] |date=March 2005 |accessdate=30 November 2009}}
&lt;/ref&gt; that is dedicated to providing the world with objective, [[science|scientific]] information relevant to understanding the scientific basis of the
risk of human-induced&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://archive.ipcc.ch/pdf/ipcc-principles/ipcc-principles.pdf|title=PRINCIPLES GOVERNING IPCC WORK|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}&lt;/ref&gt; [[climate change]], its natural, [[politics|political]], and [[economics|economic]] impacts and risks, and possible response options.&lt;ref name="Weart international 80s"&gt;
{{cite web |last = Weart | first = Spencer |authorlink=Spencer R. Weart |title = International Cooperation: Democracy and Policy Advice (1980s) |work=[[The Discovery of Global Warming]] |url = http://www.aip.org/history/climate/internat.htm#S9 | publisher = [[American Institute of Physics]] |date = December 2011 | accessdate = 9 July 2012 }}
&lt;/ref&gt;

===Environment===
* Palin supports off-shore drilling, and land-based drilling in the [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]].&lt;ref name="ANWR"/&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/25394468/Drill_Drill_Drill_My_Interview_with_Alaska_Governor_Sarah_Palin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121103101940/http://www.cnbc.com/id/25394468/Drill_Drill_Drill_My_Interview_with_Alaska_Governor_Sarah_Palin|url-status=dead|archive-date=November 3, 2012|title=Drill, Drill, Drill: My Interview with Alaska Governor Sarah Palin|last=Kudlow|first=Larry|work=Money &amp; Politics|date=June 26, 2008|publisher=CNBC|accessdate=May 29, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; When commenting on the Gulf Coast oil disaster Palin said, "I repeat the slogan 'drill here, drill now.{{'"}}&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|first=David|last=Weigel|date=April 30, 2010|work=[[The Washington Post]]|url=http://voices.washingtonpost.com/right-now/2010/04/palin_on_oil_spill_no_human_en.html|title=Palin on oil spill: 'No human endeavor is ever without risk'|department=Right Now|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; She said, "I want our country to be able to trust the oil industry."&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.kansascity.com/2010/05/01/1916939/key-to-us-prosperity-is-energy.html|title=Key to U.S. prosperity is energy security, Palin says during speech in Independence|last=Kraske|first=Steve|date=May 1, 2010|newspaper=The Kansas City Star|accessdate=May 28, 2010|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100504144058/http://www.kansascity.com/2010/05/01/1916939/key-to-us-prosperity-is-energy.html | archivedate = May 4, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; Palin asked supporters to read an article by [[Thomas Sowell]] that criticized Obama for having BP pay to an [[escrow]] fund.&lt;ref&gt;Politico, June 26, 2010, [http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0610/39030.html Sarah Palin praises column linking Obama, Hitler]&lt;/ref&gt;
* Palin considers herself a [[Conservation movement|conservationist]]&lt;ref name=SnakeOil&gt;{{cite news|title=Palin: Global Warming Just "Snake Oil"|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/palin-global-warming-just-snake-oil/|publisher=CBS News|agency=Associated Press|accessdate=March 12, 2014|date=February 9, 2010|quote=I named my daughter Willow. Isn't that granola enough for them?}}&lt;/ref&gt;  and during the 2008 campaign demonstrated her [[global warming skepticism|skepticism]] about [[global warming|global warming politics]],&lt;ref name="anthroGW"&gt;{{cite news|accessdate=May 28, 2010|url=http://www.newsmax.com/Headline/sarah-palin-vp/2008/08/29/id/325086|last=Coppock|first=Mike|title=Palin Speaks to Newsmax About McCain, Abortion, Climate Change|publisher=Newsmax|date=August 29, 2008|quote=A changing environment will affect Alaska more than any other state...I'm not one though who would attribute it to being man-made}}&lt;/ref&gt; saying "of global warming, climate change, whether it's entirely, wholly caused by man's activities or is part of the cyclical nature of our planet...John McCain and I agree that we have to make sure that we're doing all we can to cut down on pollution."&lt;ref name="Palin Goldman"&gt;{{cite news|url=http://abcnews.go.com/print?id=5778018|title=Palin Takes Hard Line on National Security, Softens Stance on Global Warming| publisher=ABC News|author=Goldman, Russell|date= September 11, 2008|accessdate=May 28, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; She opposed [[cap-and-trade]] proposals contained in the yet to be defeated [[American Clean Energy and Security Act|ACES energy bill]].&lt;ref name=CapandTax&gt;{{cite news|last=Palin|first=Sarah|title=A 'Cap and Tax' Road to Economic Disaster|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/13/AR2009071302852.html?sid=ST2009071302882|accessdate=March 12, 2014|newspaper=Washington Post Op-ed|date=July 14, 2009|quote=Consequently, many of us ... recognize that the president's cap-and-trade energy tax would adversely affect every aspect of the U.S. economy}}&lt;/ref&gt; Speaking at a 2009 Department of Interior hearing, Palin acknowledged that "many believe" a global effort to reduce greenhouse gases is needed. She stated, "[S]topping domestic energy production of preferred fuels does not solve the issues associated with global warming and threatened or endangered species, but it can make them worse ... These available fuels are required to supply the nation's energy needs during the transition to green energy alternatives."&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/apr/15/nation/na-palin15|title=Palin sees gas drilling as step to curb global warming|work=Los Angeles Times|date=April 15, 2009|accessdate=August 15, 2010|first=Kim|last=Murphy}}&lt;/ref&gt; After the election and the [[Climatic Research Unit email controversy|Climategate scandal]], Palin spoke at a 2010 California logging conference calling studies supporting global climate change as "snake oil science". She criticized heavy-handed environmental laws and cited her 2008 suit, as Alaska's governor, against the federal government to overturn [[Polar bear#Conservation status, threats and controversies|the listing of polar bears as a threatened species]]. She considered environmental regulations as an economic burden to businesses trying to recover from the recession and environmental activists as wanting to "lock up the land".&lt;ref name=SnakeOil/&gt;

